  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Cheesemaking at Home</h1>
      <h2>
        What's not to love about cheese? <br />
        <br />
      </h2>
      <p>
        <img
          src="https://www.greekboston.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/feta-cheese-720x480.jpg"
          alt="Feta in cubes"
          width="700px"
        />
      </p>
      <h3>
        If you find yourself wondering how your favourite type of cheese is
        made, the best way to find out is to try making it yourself. Before you
        know it, you'll have delicious homemade cheese to feast on and brag
        about!
      </h3>
      <h2>All you need is 3 basic ingredients.</h2>
      <h3>
        First, <strong>good milk</strong> - duh. Always non ultra-pasteurized.
        <strong>Always.</strong> <br />For soft types of cheese, you'll need
        whole milk. <br />
        For harder types of cheese, skim milk might be preferred. <br />Milk
        from cows, sheep, and goats tastes different - and so does cheese.
        <br />
        <br />
        Second, a <strong>coagulant substance</strong>. Either enzyme coagulant
        (rennet) or acid.<br />
        It's this substance that causes the solids in the milk to curdle
        together. <br />Try pouring lemon juice in hot milk and watch it curdle.
        <br />That's right, cheesemaking can be as easy as that.
        <br />
        <br />
        Third, <strong> heat</strong>. Each cheese requires heating the milk to
        <strong>specific temperatures</strong>. <br />When the right temperature
        is reached, the milk proteins are denatured. <br />Then, the coagulant
        kicks in and works its magic... and Voila!
      </h3>
      <p>
        <button>
          <a
            href="https://www.cheesescience.org/coagulation.html"
            target="_blank"
            class="link"
          >
            Learn more about cheese coagulation
          </a>
        </button>
      </p>
